gd Koninkrijk","Eaton, Cheshire, England":"Eaton, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1260–1292":"1260–1292","1265–1316":"1265–1316","1278–Female":"1278–Deceased","1285–1349":"1285–1349","1291–1332":"1291–1332","1227–1272":"1227–1272","1240–1293":"1240–1293","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","1293":"1293","1292":"1292","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1316":"1316","1227":"1227","Abt 1278":"about 1278","1278":"1278","1332":"1332","1265":"1265","Stockport, Cheshire, England":"Stockport, Cheshire, England","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England","Of,, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Eaton, Cheshire, England":"Eaton, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Stockport","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Stopford  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stopford","meanings":["English: locative name from Stockport (Cheshire), which is recorded as  <i>Stokeport</i> in 1188,  <i>Stockford</i> in 1283–8,  <i>Stopford</i> in 1347,  <i>Stoppord</i> in 1337, and  <i>Stapporte</i> in 1583."]}]},{"name":"Third","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish: locative name from one or more of various minor places so called because they were at one time farms divided among three tenants."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Baron","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French, English, Dutch, Polish, Czech, Romanian, and Croatian; Breton (also <b>Le Baron</b>): from Old French <i>barun</i>, <i>baron</i>, Middle English <i>barun</i>, <i>baroun</i>, Middle Dutch <i>baroen</i>, Polish, Czech, Romanian, and dialectal Croatian <i>baron</i> ‘baron’ (i.e. a nobleman ranking below an earl and above a knight), a title of nobility which was in England also awarded to certain freemen of the cities of London and York and of the Cinque Ports. As a surname it is unlikely to be a status name denoting a person of rank. Generally, it referred to service in a baronial household or was acquired as a nickname by a peasant who had ideas above his station or applied to a man showing characteristics of a nobleman. See also 3 and 4 below, compare   Barron   and   Lebaron  .","French: habitational name from (Le) Baron, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Lebaron  .","German: status name for a freeman or baron, from <i>barūn</i> ‘imperial or church official’, a loanword in Middle High German from Old French (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Barron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Jesus, Manuel, Francisco, Carlos, Miguel, Raul, Pedro, Ruben, Alfredo, Luis.","Scottish: status name from Scots <i>baron</i>, which in the Highlands denoted a small proprietary landholder. In Angus it alluded specifically to a tenant of one of the small baronies attached to the Abbey of Coupar Angus. The surname was taken by Scottish migrants to Ulster. Compare   Baron  .","Scottish: shortened form of <b>McBarron</b>, from Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac a' Bharain</b> ‘son of the baron’. See   Baron   and 1 above."]},{"name":"Boron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Krystyna, Edyta, Leszek, Mieczyslaw, Mieczyslawa, Wladyslaw.","Polish (<b>Boroń</b>): from a pet form of the personal names <i>Borzysław</i> or <i>Borzymir</i>, formed with the element <i>bor</i> ‘to fight’ (from Old Slavic <i>boriti se</i>).","French: habitational name from a place so called in Franche-Comté."]},{"name":"Baro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Mario, Manuel, Ana, Angel, Carlos, Cesar, Fernando, Jesus, Jose, Orlando, Ramon, Rosalia.  Italian Guido, Angelo, Carmelo, Federico, Lucio.","Catalan (<b>Baró</b>): status name from <i>baró</i> ‘free man, baron’ (see   Baron   1), or a habitational name from a place so named.","Hungarian (<b>Báró</b>): status name from <i>báró</i> ‘baron’. In the form <b>Baró</b>, it could be from a pet form of the personal names <i>Barabás</i> (see   Barabas  ) or <i>Bertalan</i>."]},{"name":"Barona","meanings":["Spanish: from the feminine form of <b>Barón</b> ‘baron’ (see   Baron  ), applied as a nickname or as an occupational name for a member of the household of a baroness.","Italian: probably from the feminine form of   Barone  . The name is concentrated in Sondrio province (Lombardy)."]},{"name":"Barren","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Baron   or   Barran  ."]}]},{"name":"Stockport","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Stopford  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stopford","meanings":["English: locative name from Stockport (Cheshire), which is recorded as  <i>Stokeport</i> in 1188,  <i>Stockford</i> in 1283–8,  <i>Stopford</i> in 1347,  <i>Stoppord</i> in 1337, and  <i>Stapporte</i> in 1583."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":30,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard de Stockport - Third Baron Stockport was born in 1260, in Stockport, Cheshire, England, his father, Sir Robert III de Stockport - Second Baron Stockport, was 33 and his mother, Elene de Maubanc, was 20. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Cecilia de Huxlegh. He died in 1292, in his hometown, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1260–1292":"1260–1292","1265–1316":"1265–1316","1278–Female":"1278–Surnud","1285–1349":"1285–1349","129